â˜ï¸ Cloud Service Models
Cloud providers offer different levels of services depending on how much control and responsibility you want. These models are:

IaaS â€“ Infrastructure as a Service
PaaS â€“ Platform as a Service
SaaS â€“ Software as a Service


ğŸ§± What is IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service)?
####################################################
-> IaaS is a cloud service model where the cloud provider gives you raw infrastructure, and you build everything on top of it.

ğŸ—ï¸ Think of it like:
"You rent a fully functional empty building, and itâ€™s your job to furnish it, decorate it, and use it however you want."

âœ… What the cloud provider gives you:
---------------------------------------------
ğŸ–¥ï¸ Virtual Machines (VMs)
ğŸŒ Networking (IP, firewall, load balancer)
ğŸ’¾ Storage (hard drives, SSDs)
âš™ï¸ Virtualization, Servers, Data Center

âœ… What you (the customer) have to do:
------------------------------------------------
Install Operating System (e.g., Ubuntu, Windows)
Install runtime environments (Java, Python, Node.js, etc.)
Set up web servers (Apache, Nginx, Tomcat, etc.)
Deploy and manage your application code
Handle updates, patches, and security

ğŸ“¦ Example Scenario
----------------------------------
Letâ€™s say you want to host a Java web application.

Using IaaS:
------------
You create a VM on AWS EC2
Install Ubuntu
Install Java, Tomcat, MySQL
Deploy your .war file
Configure your firewall, ports, etc.

ğŸ”§ Common IaaS Providers
Provider	     	Service Example
AWS			          EC2, EBS, VPC
Microsoft Azure		Virtual Machines
Google Cloud		Compute Engine
Oracle Cloud		OCI Compute
DigitalOcean		Droplets

